\end_layout

\end_inset


\color blue
In both simulations, we used as a founder population a subset of 400 SNP
 and 150 individuals from tetraploid potato data described by Enciso-Rodriguez
 et al.(2018).
 To create both simulations of phenotypes, we sampled either additive or
 dominant effects from a gamma distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma$
\end_inset

 (shape = 0.2 and scale = 5) using 50 repetitions and ten causal SNPs under
 the Phyton3 SeqBreed software (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Enciso2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), inspired in the pSBVB software created to generate polyploid data (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zingaretti2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
Both simulated data sets were analyzed in MultiGWAS using the following
 parameters: Gene action, either additive or dominant, false filtering,
 Bonferroni correction method, and Naive GWAS model using the founder genotype
 and either the additive or dominant phenotype.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
After MultiGWAS analysis, we summarized the top SNPs (i.e., the N best-ranked
 SNPs found by the tool) and significant SNPs found by each GWAS tool.
 Then, we calculated two metrics: true-positive rates (TPR) and true- negative
 rates (TNR) expressed in the following equations:
\color inherit
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align left
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textcolor{blue}{TPR=\frac{TP}{TP+FN}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
Where TP is the number of SNPs correctly identified as causal SNPs, and
 FN is the number of SNPs incorrectly identified as non-causal SNPs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textcolor{blue}{TNR=\frac{TN}{TN+FP}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
Where TN is the number of SNPs correctly identified as non-causal SNPs,
 and FP is the number of SNPs incorrectly identified as causal SNPs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
